<span id="freeTextContainer16678449422103894558">This was one of the few Crichton novels I hadn&apos;t went back and read. With the sequel coming out (<a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44148860.The_Andromeda_Evolution__Andromeda__2_' title='The Andromeda Evolution (Andromeda #2) by Daniel H. Wilson' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Andomeda Evolution</a>), I decided it was time to go back and read it. This was written 50 years ago being Crichton&apos;s first book and you can tell. The book is highly technical. It&apos;s well researched using the real science of the time, but it&apos;s packed with technical jargon, enough to bog the book down at times. The roots of a great story are there, especially the ending which is thrilling. And I like t</span>
  <span id="freeText16678449422103894558" style="display:none">This was one of the few Crichton novels I hadn't went back and read. With the sequel coming out (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44148860.The_Andromeda_Evolution__Andromeda__2_" title="The Andromeda Evolution (Andromeda #2) by Daniel H. Wilson" rel="nofollow noopener">The Andomeda Evolution</a>), I decided it was time to go back and read it. This was written 50 years ago being Crichton's first book and you can tell. The book is highly technical. It's well researched using the real science of the time, but it's packed with technical jargon, enough to bog the book down at times. The roots of a great story are there, especially the ending which is thrilling. And I like that Crichton uses a device that Stephen King also often uses, the foreboding shadow of things to come. If you're a Michael Crichton fan, this is certainly worth a read.</span>
